of cells, hence their name. There are two types of nucleic acid: DNA
and RNA. Nucleic acids are very large molecules that are constructed by
linking together nucleotides to form a polymer.

To link nucleotides together into a chain or polymer, covalent bonds are
formed between the phosphate of one nucleotide and the pentose sugar
of the next nucleotide. This creates a strong backbone for the molecule of
alternating sugar and phosphate groups, with a base linked to each sugar.
There are four different bases in both DNA and RNA, so there are four
different nucleotides. The four different nucleotides can be linked
together in any sequence, because the phosphate and sugar used to link
them are the same in every nucleotide. Any base sequence is therefore
possible along a DNA or RNA molecule. This is the key to nucleic acids
acting as a store of genetic information – the base sequence is the store
of information and the sugar phosphate backbone ensures that the store
DNA diers from RNA in the number of strands normally
present, the base composition and the type of pentose.

sugar in them – deoxyribonucleic acid and ribonucleic acid.
